                                     </dimensions>
                                    <desc type="decoration">Towards the centre of the front face are two closely packed Pictish symbols - the remains of a <rs type="decoration" key="PictishSymbol">fish</rs> and the so-called <rs type="decoration" key="PictishSymbol">rectangle</rs> (Forsyth 1996, 14).</desc>
                                </support>
                                <condition><q>The various fragments of this slab have been cemented back together, but the surface of the upper pan is missing, taking part of a symbol and perhaps part of the ogham with it. The remaining carving is clear and well-preserved</q> (Forsyth 1996, 13). Therefore, the ogham inscription may be complete as it is, but the possibility of lost letters cannot be completely ruled out (ibid).</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="other" rend="stemline_diagonal">The ogham inscription is carved towards the left edge of the front face at an acute angle and on a drawn stem-line (Forsyth 1996, 13-4). The stem stops c.6cm short of the outer edge of the stone, but nothing of the original surface remains in the area beyond the last stroke (Forsyth 1996, 16). </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The inscription was <rs type="execution"  key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked and rubbed</rs> smooth as is typical for Class I stones (Forsyth 1996, 13). 
                                <height/>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
